false sharing


Acquire locally: later operations cannot move before the load.
Acquire across threads: if the load sees a value stored with release, then prior writes from that thread become visible too.



et me break down what guard is actually protecting, because it's doing several different jobs:

1. next_dir_id / next_file_id counters (lines 110, 148)
Your instinct is right — these can be std::atomic<DirectoryId> / std::atomic<FileId> with fetch_add. No lock needed.

2. active_tasks counter (lines 117, 177, 184)
This can also be std::atomic<int>. In C++20 you get atomic::wait() and atomic::notify_one() — so the done_cv + guard for the completion check can be replaced entirely:


std::atomic<int> active_tasks{0};
// decrement: if (active_tasks.fetch_sub(1) == 1) active_tasks.notify_one();
// wait: active_tasks.wait(non_zero_value);
This removes the lock from the hot per-directory completion path entirely.

3. tree.directories[id].path read (line 71)
This is the only READ under the lock, and it's only locked because tree.directories is a std::vector that could reallocate. If you switch tree.directories to std::deque, existing element references are stable across push_back — no reallocation ever invalidates them. The read can then happen without any lock.

4. tree.directories[id].subdirs.push_back and tree.directories[id].files.push_back (lines 116, 150)
These modify a specific directory node's children. Crucially, each directory id is processed by exactly one worker — so tree.directories[id].subdirs and tree.directories[id].files are never touched by two threads simultaneously. With stable references (deque), these also need no lock.

5. tree.directories.push_back, tree.files.push_back, tree.errors.push_back (lines 115, 149, 155, 160, 168, 88, 99)
These are concurrent pushes to shared vectors from multiple workers. These still need synchronization — you can't avoid it without a fundamentally different data structure. This is where the lock genuinely earns its keep.

What this buys you:

Currently the lock is held across the entire directory-case block (lines 109–118), which includes ID generation, vector push, AND subdirs.push_back. After these changes, the lock is held only for the actual push_back to the shared vectors — the minimum possible critical section.

The active_tasks atomic + wait/notify removes the lock entirely from the completion tracking path, which is taken once per directory.

The remaining lock on push_back is unavoidable without switching to a lock-free concurrent queue for tree.directories, tree.files, and tree.errors — which would be a much larger change and likely not worth it given the I/O dominates anyway.






mordern cpp
Genuine opportunities
1. std::expected in the parser — this is the biggest one
ParseResult has a success bool + errors vector — that's exactly what std::expected was designed to replace. The individual handlers like parse_positive_size could return std::expected<size_t, std::string> instead of returning 0 and side-effecting into an error list. Cleaner call sites, no implicit sentinel values.

2. Concepts on LockFreeDeque and ThreadPool
The static_assert pair in the deque:


static_assert(std::is_trivially_copyable_v<T>, ...);
static_assert(std::is_trivially_destructible_v<T>, ...);
is exactly what a concept expresses — and you get the constraint at the point of instantiation with a cleaner error. Same for ThreadPool<Handler> — a std::invocable<Handler, DirectoryId> constraint makes the template's expectation explicit.

3. std::print / std::println in view.cpp
You're already using std::format — C++23 std::print is the natural next step. Eliminates the std::cout << std::format(...) pattern entirely.

4. Ranges pipelines in analyzer.cpp
compute_recent_files, compute_symlinks, compute_empty_directories are all filter → sort → return operations on vectors. These map directly to std::ranges::filter_view pipelines. compute_largest_N_files uses std::partial_sort_copy which could become a ranges partial sort. These are already the kind of thing you'd write with ranges naturally.

5. std::flat_map for extension stats
compute_extension_stats builds an unordered_map then sorts at the end. Since you always end up with a sorted output, std::flat_map (C++23) — which is a sorted, contiguous key-value structure — fits better and has better cache behaviour.

What probably doesn't fit
Coroutines / std::async: Your work-stealing scheduler is strictly better than std::async for this use case — you have a warm thread pool, balanced load, and no per-task thread overhead. Coroutines would add complexity without throughput gains since the bottleneck is filesystem I/O, not scheduling overhead. The learning you did on lock-free structures is the right tool here.

std::jthread in Worker: Could replace std::thread and the manual joinable() check in the destructor since jthread auto-joins, but it's a minor cosmetic change given you already handle it correctly.

std::mdspan: No multi-dimensional data here.

Summary
Feature	Where	Value
std::expected	parser	High — replaces error-flag + side-effects pattern
Concepts	deque, scheduler	Medium — cleaner than static_assert
std::print	view	Low effort, natural upgrade
Ranges pipelines	analyzer	Medium — cleaner filter/sort chains
std::flat_map	analyzer extension stats	Low-medium — cache win, fits the usage
The parser std::expected refactor is the one I'd do first — it changes the design in a meaningful way. The rest are refinements.



emory allocator — slab allocator or jemalloc-style. Directly extends your cache-line alignment and atomics work. You understand alignas(64) — now understand mmap, brk, fragmentation, and thread-local caches.
Simple kernel — OSDev (osdev.org). Boot, protected mode, paging tables, interrupt handlers, your own context switcher. This is where the OS scheduler you've been reasoning about actually lives.
Write-ahead log — how databases survive crashes. fsync semantics, mmap vs write, memory-mapped files, crash consistency.